kmod-amneziawg: explicitly pass the kernel's own Module.symvers

modpost fails with:

  ERROR: modpost: "chacha20poly1305_encrypt_sg_inplace" [amneziawg.ko] undefined!
  ERROR: modpost: "curve25519" [amneziawg.ko] undefined!
  ...

These are not a kernel-6.18 API drift: lib/crypto/chacha20poly1305.c
in mainline 6.18.38 (hash ac26e508... pinned by
target/linux/generic/kernel-6.18 in this fork) still exports every
one of these names via plain EXPORT_SYMBOL, unnamespaced. The module
compiles cleanly (main.o..junk.o, LD amneziawg.o) - this is purely a
link-time symbol visibility problem.

Per include/kernel.mk in this fork:
  - KBUILD_EXTRA_SYMBOLS normally auto-expands to
    $(wildcard $(KERNEL_BUILD_DIR)/symvers/*.symvers) (kernel.mk:118).
  - Individual kmod packages populate that directory via the
    collect_module_symvers post-compile hook - but that hook is
    explicitly skipped when PKG_NAME is "kernel" (kernel.mk:158).
  - kmod-udptunnel4/6 and kmod-crypto-lib-chacha20poly1305/curve25519
    are all defined in package/kernel/linux/modules/*.mk and built as
    part of the single combined package/kernel/linux compile pass
    (PKG_NAME=kernel there), so they never get a
    $(KERNEL_BUILD_DIR)/symvers/<name>.symvers snapshot - by design,
    their exports are meant to be picked up from the kernel's own
    $(LINUX_DIR)/Module.symvers, which any M= external-module build
    reads automatically without needing KBUILD_EXTRA_SYMBOLS at all.

That automatic pickup evidently isn't happening for this package (two
earlier attempts guessing at nonexistent per-package snapshot files -
$(LINUX_DIR)/symvers/*.symvers and $(LINUX_DIR)/../symvers/*.symvers -
both confirmed those files simply don't exist for these four
packages). Pass $(LINUX_DIR)/Module.symvers explicitly as a
belt-and-suspenders fix.

--- a/kmod-amneziawg/Makefile
+++ b/kmod-amneziawg/Makefile
@@ -39,6 +39,7 @@
 		M="$(PKG_BUILD_DIR)/$(MAKE_PATH)" \
 		EXTRA_CFLAGS="$(BUILDFLAGS)" \
 		WIREGUARD_VERSION="$(WIREGUARD_VERSION)" \
+		KBUILD_EXTRA_SYMBOLS="$(LINUX_DIR)/Module.symvers" \
 		modules
 endef
